\section{Case Study Overview}

The Amazon Black Friday Sale 2026 represents a high-uncertainty, high-load system scenario, where extreme traffic spikes—not average behavior—determine system failure.

Traffic arrivals follow a Poisson process. System failure occurs when requests exceed a critical threshold $k$.

The central quantity of interest is:
\[
P(X \geq k)
\]

Even if the mean $\lambda = 50$ is safe, the system fails due to tail probability, not expectation.

\textbf{Key Insight:}
System reliability is governed by the tail, not the mean.

\section{Mathematical Foundation of Tail Bounds}

We aim to estimate:
\[
P(X \geq k)
\]

\subsection{Markov’s Inequality}

For a non-negative random variable $X$:
\[
P(X \geq a) \leq \frac{\mathbb{E}[X]}{a}
\]

\textbf{Requirements:} Mean $\mu = \mathbb{E}[X]$

\textbf{Behavior:} Linear decay $\frac{1}{k}$

\subsection{Chebyshev’s Inequality}

\[
P(|X - \mu| \geq a) \leq \frac{\sigma^2}{a^2}
\]

Equivalent form:
\[
P(X \geq a) \leq \frac{\sigma^2}{(a - \mu)^2}
\]

\textbf{Requirements:} Mean $\mu$, Variance $\sigma^2$

\textbf{Behavior:} Polynomial decay $\frac{1}{k^2}$

\subsection{Chernoff Bound}

General form:
\[
P(X \geq a) \leq \min_{t > 0} e^{-ta} M_X(t)
\]

where
\[
M_X(t) = \mathbb{E}[e^{tX}]
\]

Derived exponential form:
\[
P(X \geq a) \leq e^{-k(\ln r - r + 1)}
\]

\textbf{Requirements:} Moment Generating Function (MGF)

\textbf{Behavior:} Exponential decay $e^{-k}$

\section{Comparative Analysis: Race to Zero}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}
\hline
\textbf{Bound} & \textbf{Decay Type} & \textbf{Behavior} \\
\hline
Markov & Linear & Slow decay \\
Chebyshev & Polynomial & Moderate decay \\
Chernoff & Exponential & Fast decay \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\textbf{Insight:} More information leads to tighter bounds:
\[
\text{Markov} \rightarrow \text{Chebyshev} \rightarrow \text{Chernoff}
\]

\section{System Reliability Metrics}

Example:
\[
\lambda = 500, \quad k = 600
\]

We estimate:
\[
P(X \geq 600)
\]

